1
00:00:14,700 --> 00:00:21,500
ONLY YESTERDAY

2
00:02:08,530 --> 00:02:12,950
With ten days off,
I figured you'd go abroad.

3
00:02:13,030 --> 00:02:15,780
But you're off to Yamagata, right?

4
00:02:15,870 --> 00:02:16,870
Yes.

5
00:02:16,950 --> 00:02:18,200
Broke up with your boyfriend?

6
00:02:20,540 --> 00:02:22,120
I just prefer the countryside.

7
00:02:22,210 --> 00:02:23,750
-See ya!
-Bye!

8
00:02:23,830 --> 00:02:24,920
Let's go to your place!

9
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:26,590
-No way.
-Why?

10
00:02:26,670 --> 00:02:29,460
-Because...
-Later!

11
00:02:29,550 --> 00:02:30,840
Did you get good grades?

12
00:02:31,340 --> 00:02:34,050
No, but I don't care.

13
00:02:34,140 --> 00:02:35,140
How come?

14
00:02:35,220 --> 00:02:38,310
As soon as I get home,
we're traveling to Grandma's.

15
00:02:38,390 --> 00:02:40,770
So I won't get yelled at for ages.

16
00:02:40,850 --> 00:02:44,020
Lucky you! Are you going away too?

17
00:02:44,100 --> 00:02:46,900
Yeah, to Nagano. How about you, Taeko?

18
00:02:46,980 --> 00:02:47,900
I'm not sure.

19
00:02:48,270 --> 00:02:50,610
My dad bought a summer home.

20
00:02:50,900 --> 00:02:52,400
Wow... that's great.

21
00:02:54,450 --> 00:02:57,240
Such a bad grade in math again.

22
00:02:58,910 --> 00:03:00,830
But I got a "B" in science.

23
00:03:01,450 --> 00:03:04,040
Are we going away for the vacation?

24
00:03:04,120 --> 00:03:05,290
Not really.

25
00:03:05,830 --> 00:03:08,130
Take me someplace.

26
00:03:08,880 --> 00:03:13,380
I'll take you to a movie.
How about "The Crane Lady"?

27
00:03:13,470 --> 00:03:16,430
Not that. I mean to the country...

28
00:03:16,510 --> 00:03:17,550
The country?

29
00:03:17,640 --> 00:03:19,970
Like Grandma's country house.

30
00:03:20,060 --> 00:03:21,560
Grandma lives with us.

31
00:03:21,640 --> 00:03:24,060
-Grandpa's then...
-He's dead.

32
00:03:24,140 --> 00:03:27,650
We don't have relatives
in the country, so don't ask.

33
00:03:32,400 --> 00:03:35,910
<i>My family had lived in Tokyo</i>
<i>for generations.</i>

34
00:03:36,360 --> 00:03:39,280
<i>I envied friends who had family</i>
<i>in the countryside.</i>

35
00:03:42,450 --> 00:03:45,420
It's too late to book.
All hotels will be full.

36
00:03:46,040 --> 00:03:47,420
But I really want to go...

37
00:03:48,590 --> 00:03:50,380
-What about Onoya?
-Huh?

38
00:03:50,460 --> 00:03:54,550
We're regulars. They'd have a room for us.

39
00:03:54,630 --> 00:03:55,880
Where's that?

40
00:03:55,970 --> 00:03:59,390
Good idea. Taeko's never been there.

41
00:03:59,470 --> 00:04:00,680
That's right.

42
00:04:00,760 --> 00:04:03,180
Is it in the mountains? By the sea?

43
00:04:03,930 --> 00:04:05,060
It's in Atami.

44
00:04:06,690 --> 00:04:07,850
Atami?

45
00:04:07,940 --> 00:04:10,400
You get to ride the bullet train.

46
00:04:10,650 --> 00:04:12,480
Sure, you'll love it.

47
00:04:16,320 --> 00:04:17,410
Atami...

48
00:04:17,490 --> 00:04:20,120
It's great!
Lots of different hot springs...

49
00:04:20,530 --> 00:04:23,620
There's the huge Roman Bath.

50
00:04:23,700 --> 00:04:29,540
And other little ones, like
the Swan Bath and the Violet Bath.

51
00:04:29,630 --> 00:04:31,250
The beautiful Violet Bath!

52
00:04:32,500 --> 00:04:33,590
The Violet Bath...

53
00:04:33,880 --> 00:04:36,090
Oh yes. It's fantastic.

54
00:04:36,170 --> 00:04:37,930
You love hot springs, right?

55
00:04:38,380 --> 00:04:42,390
Since Father's working, you four go.

56
00:04:42,970 --> 00:04:43,850
What?

57
00:04:47,600 --> 00:04:48,980
Us?

58
00:04:49,060 --> 00:04:50,270
Go too?

59
00:04:57,200 --> 00:05:01,070
I'm amazed you show up every morning.

60
00:05:01,160 --> 00:05:03,580
Everyone else has left town.

61
00:05:05,790 --> 00:05:08,160
Aren't you going anywhere?

62
00:05:08,750 --> 00:05:10,120
-Yes, I am.
-Where?

63
00:05:10,210 --> 00:05:11,210
Atami.

64
00:05:11,580 --> 00:05:14,670
Atami? What's in Atami?

65
00:05:14,750 --> 00:05:16,340
Hot springs.

66
00:05:20,510 --> 00:05:22,100
It's good timing.

67
00:05:22,180 --> 00:05:25,770
We're going away next week
to visit relatives.

68
00:05:26,350 --> 00:05:29,640
No one will be around for ages.

69
00:05:32,610 --> 00:05:34,360
<i>Hello. Okajima residence.</i>

70
00:05:34,940 --> 00:05:37,240
Nanako? It's Taeko.

71
00:05:37,490 --> 00:05:41,530
I leave today. Any messages for
your husband's family?

72
00:05:42,530 --> 00:05:47,080
<i>Not really. Just bring them something.</i>
<i>Maybe cookies.</i>

73
00:05:47,160 --> 00:05:50,250
<i>Say it's from us and I'll pay you back.</i>

74
00:05:50,330 --> 00:05:53,500
Don't worry about it. How's Mom?

75
00:05:53,580 --> 00:05:55,000
<i>She's out today.</i>

76
00:05:55,210 --> 00:05:59,170
<i>She was mad you turned down</i>
<i>that guy's proposal.</i>

77
00:05:59,760 --> 00:06:03,510
<i>"At 27, that's the best offer</i>
<i>she's going to get!"</i>

78
00:06:03,590 --> 00:06:06,260
It's all she talks about.

79
00:06:06,350 --> 00:06:10,270
<i>She's got a point.</i>
<i>You're not young anymore.</i>

80
00:06:10,350 --> 00:06:11,560
Oh, yeah?

81
00:06:11,640 --> 00:06:13,150
<i>Definitely.</i>

82
00:06:13,230 --> 00:06:15,610
<i>You've got to settle down eventually.</i>

83
00:06:15,690 --> 00:06:20,240
<i>By the way, did you really work</i>
<i>in the fields last year?</i>

84
00:06:20,320 --> 00:06:23,990
Yes, harvesting rice.
This year, I'm picking safflower.

85
00:06:24,070 --> 00:06:25,070
<i>Safflower?</i>

86
00:06:25,160 --> 00:06:29,160
Thanks to you, I finally have family
in the countryside.

87
00:06:29,250 --> 00:06:32,670
So, I'm making the most of it!

88
00:06:34,210 --> 00:06:35,840
<i>Give me a break!</i>

89
00:06:36,340 --> 00:06:39,800
<i>Rather than stay in that old house,</i>

90
00:06:39,880 --> 00:06:43,840
<i>why not treat yourself</i>
<i>to a fancy hotel for once?</i>

91
00:06:43,930 --> 00:06:45,970
Maybe you'd meet a nice boy.

92
00:06:46,350 --> 00:06:50,810
No way. You mean a hotel like Onoya?

93
00:06:50,890 --> 00:06:52,140
<i>Onoya?</i>

94
00:06:54,560 --> 00:06:56,400
<i>Not that again!</i>

95
00:06:57,360 --> 00:06:59,900
<i>You've got to get over it.</i>

96
00:06:59,980 --> 00:07:03,070
<i>Let go of that baggage from the past!</i>

97
00:07:12,830 --> 00:07:17,250
<i>My sisters, of course, would never go</i>
<i>to a place like Atami.</i>

98
00:07:19,050 --> 00:07:21,300
Grandma...

99
00:07:22,420 --> 00:07:24,180
Almost done?

100
00:07:25,180 --> 00:07:27,010
Let's go to another bath.

101
00:07:27,100 --> 00:07:29,510
We just went.

102
00:07:29,600 --> 00:07:31,930
Only to the Swan Bath.

103
00:07:34,390 --> 00:07:38,690
<i>Bored to tears, I went alone</i>
<i>to the Brothers Grimm Bath,</i>

104
00:07:39,270 --> 00:07:41,690
<i>the Mermaid Bath, the Lemon Bath,</i>

105
00:07:42,280 --> 00:07:45,700
<i>and the Violet Bath, one after the other.</i>

106
00:07:45,780 --> 00:07:47,740
It's enormous!

107
00:07:48,320 --> 00:07:51,700
<i>When I got to the Roman Bath,</i>
<i>my head was spinning.</i>

108
00:07:53,410 --> 00:07:55,290
It's amazing...

109
00:08:05,510 --> 00:08:07,090
<i>And I fainted.</i>

110
00:08:08,050 --> 00:08:10,600
<i>And with that, my trip was over.</i>

111
00:08:10,680 --> 00:08:14,310
<i>Followed by endless weeks of vacation.</i>

112
00:08:14,390 --> 00:08:16,020
<i>Jump on both feet.</i>

113
00:08:24,070 --> 00:08:25,860
<i>Now your arms and legs.</i>

114
00:08:28,950 --> 00:08:34,080
<i>The other day,</i>
<i>my sisters and I were reminiscing.</i>

115
00:08:35,540 --> 00:08:38,960
<i>We couldn't stop laughing</i>

116
00:08:39,460 --> 00:08:41,960
<i>as the memories came flooding back.</i>

117
00:08:47,630 --> 00:08:48,840
Had one before?

118
00:08:48,930 --> 00:08:50,510
No, it's my first time.

119
00:08:51,050 --> 00:08:52,760
I'm the one who asked for it.

120
00:08:52,850 --> 00:08:54,100
Yeah, we know.

121
00:08:54,180 --> 00:08:55,980
Where did you buy it?

122
00:08:56,560 --> 00:08:57,940
Senbikiya in Ginza.

123
00:08:58,020 --> 00:08:59,400
Must have been expensive.

124
00:09:00,980 --> 00:09:02,690
How do we eat it?

125
00:09:02,770 --> 00:09:04,030
Slice it into rings.

126
00:09:04,110 --> 00:09:05,030
But how?

127
00:09:07,610 --> 00:09:08,610
I don't know.

128
00:09:10,280 --> 00:09:13,030
Didn't you ask in the store?

129
00:09:18,410 --> 00:09:20,460
We'll eat it next Sunday.

130
00:09:20,540 --> 00:09:22,840
Why not now?

131
00:09:23,630 --> 00:09:25,510
We don't know how.

132
00:09:28,420 --> 00:09:30,260
I'll have a banana.

133
00:09:30,340 --> 00:09:31,930
Me too.

134
00:09:35,520 --> 00:09:39,730
Strange fruit they have
in those hot countries.

135
00:09:42,730 --> 00:09:43,980
I'm home!

136
00:09:44,520 --> 00:09:46,360
I know how to eat the pineapple!

137
00:09:46,610 --> 00:09:47,780
Really?

138
00:09:52,660 --> 00:09:53,910
I'll take that.

139
00:09:54,780 --> 00:09:56,120
Mind your fingers.

140
00:09:56,200 --> 00:09:58,080
Wouldn't a carving knife be best?

141
00:10:11,680 --> 00:10:13,550
What a nice smell.

142
00:10:22,940 --> 00:10:24,770
It smells so good.

143
00:10:27,440 --> 00:10:28,690
I see.

144
00:10:29,940 --> 00:10:31,450
Get plates. Quick.

145
00:10:31,530 --> 00:10:33,700
Okay.

146
00:10:35,620 --> 00:10:37,700
Let us eat.

147
00:10:58,600 --> 00:10:59,850
It's chewy.

148
00:11:04,650 --> 00:11:06,150
Nothing special.

149
00:11:06,480 --> 00:11:08,150
Not so sweet.

150
00:11:08,230 --> 00:11:10,280
Nothing like the canned stuff.

151
00:11:10,360 --> 00:11:13,280
Live long enough and you see
lots of different things.

152
00:11:19,450 --> 00:11:21,580
-You can have mine.
-Mine too.

153
00:11:51,480 --> 00:11:52,820
It's delicious...

154
00:11:58,700 --> 00:12:01,040
Don't force yourself.

155
00:12:01,120 --> 00:12:02,160
You'll get a stomachache.

156
00:12:11,630 --> 00:12:14,840
What a letdown.

157
00:12:17,550 --> 00:12:19,850
Bananas taste much better.

158
00:12:19,930 --> 00:12:21,220
You're so right.

159
00:12:21,310 --> 00:12:24,390
Bananas are still the king of fruit.

160
00:12:24,480 --> 00:12:25,640
I'll have one now.

161
00:12:29,480 --> 00:12:35,610
<i>If you had to deceive me</i>

162
00:12:37,110 --> 00:12:42,200
<i>I wish that you had deceived me</i>

163
00:12:42,700 --> 00:12:46,540
<i>Until my death</i>

164
00:12:47,710 --> 00:12:50,330
<i>A red-ruby...</i>

165
00:12:50,420 --> 00:12:56,090
The king of fruit is...

166
00:12:56,720 --> 00:12:57,930
<i>the banana, after all.</i>

167
00:12:58,010 --> 00:13:00,630
BEST SELLING PRODUCT

168
00:13:03,810 --> 00:13:08,060
<i>The year I fainted at the baths</i>
<i>and had my first pineapple...</i>

169
00:13:08,980 --> 00:13:13,320
<i>the Beatles came to Japan,</i>
<i>and started the rock 'n' roll band</i>

170
00:13:13,400 --> 00:13:15,900
<i>and electric guitar craze.</i>

171
00:13:19,860 --> 00:13:24,330
<i>My sister Nanako, a freshman</i>
<i>in art school, was up on all the trends.</i>

172
00:13:25,410 --> 00:13:27,790
Yeah, the Beatles' lyrics are great.

173
00:13:27,870 --> 00:13:29,920
<i>When she wore a mini-skirt,</i>

174
00:13:30,250 --> 00:13:35,210
<i>she'd cover her bottom</i>
<i>going up the stairs.</i>

175
00:13:38,420 --> 00:13:43,930
<i>My clever sister, Yaeko, was crazy</i>
<i>about some Takarazuka actress.</i>

176
00:13:44,010 --> 00:13:45,350
Yaeko...

177
00:13:46,270 --> 00:13:48,350
I told you to knock!

178
00:13:52,690 --> 00:13:57,740
<i>My sisters' memories</i>
<i>are mainly of fashion and pop trends.</i>

179
00:13:58,650 --> 00:14:03,410
<i>For them, 1966 is the height of nostalgia.</i>

180
00:14:03,820 --> 00:14:07,120
<i>Whereas I was only ten years old.</i>

181
00:14:08,450 --> 00:14:12,210
<i>My favorite band had yet to debut...</i>

182
00:14:12,290 --> 00:14:17,090
<i>My only memories are the back</i>
<i>and forth between school and home.</i>

183
00:14:17,170 --> 00:14:18,880
Mine was pinned on the wall!

184
00:14:19,220 --> 00:14:21,180
That's nice.

185
00:14:21,840 --> 00:14:25,810
And it might be entered
in an essay contest.

186
00:14:25,890 --> 00:14:28,350
The teacher said to take good care of it.

187
00:14:29,060 --> 00:14:32,230
-I'd be so happy...
-You didn't finish lunch again.

188
00:14:33,190 --> 00:14:35,520
Why do you hide the pickles
inside the bread?

189
00:14:35,610 --> 00:14:37,570
'Cause I hate them.

190
00:14:37,650 --> 00:14:41,030
I've got to throw it away. What a waste.

191
00:14:41,950 --> 00:14:43,660
Such a picky eater!

192
00:14:44,620 --> 00:14:46,990
I'd rather you were a good eater

193
00:14:47,080 --> 00:14:50,660
than a good essay writer.

194
00:15:07,180 --> 00:15:10,390
How can you drink that horrible stuff?

195
00:15:12,140 --> 00:15:16,060
Milk's okay. It's onions I hate.

196
00:15:16,150 --> 00:15:19,650
I'm leaving carrots so I've got no choice.

197
00:15:20,650 --> 00:15:25,200
Who decided we can only leave one thing?

198
00:15:25,280 --> 00:15:26,450
Shall I drink it?

199
00:15:26,530 --> 00:15:27,660
Would you?

200
00:15:28,200 --> 00:15:31,000
You'll eat my onions next time?

201
00:15:39,630 --> 00:15:40,460
Thank you.

202
00:15:43,550 --> 00:15:45,720
-Carrots?
-We're allowed one thing!

203
00:15:55,230 --> 00:15:56,980
Two bowls is gross.

204
00:15:58,020 --> 00:16:00,480
People who run in the hall

205
00:16:00,820 --> 00:16:05,610
when the hall monitor says stop
should be punished.

206
00:16:06,280 --> 00:16:09,330
How are you gonna do that?

207
00:16:09,410 --> 00:16:11,120
They shouldn't do it.

208
00:16:11,490 --> 00:16:12,410
That's right.

209
00:16:12,790 --> 00:16:14,660
You might bump into someone.

210
00:16:14,750 --> 00:16:19,040
If I bumped into you I'd bounce a mile!

211
00:16:19,130 --> 00:16:20,170
Get lost!

212
00:16:20,420 --> 00:16:21,340
Oof.

213
00:16:22,210 --> 00:16:24,880
Running is no big deal.

214
00:16:24,970 --> 00:16:25,930
I agree!

215
00:16:26,010 --> 00:16:27,970
-Let's change the rule.
-But we already decided.

216
00:16:28,050 --> 00:16:29,550
What's the big deal?

217
00:16:30,350 --> 00:16:32,310
Raise your hand if you want to speak.

218
00:16:32,970 --> 00:16:34,480
-Here!
-Miss Tani.

219
00:16:36,640 --> 00:16:40,480
The hall monitor
should chase the offenders,

220
00:16:40,560 --> 00:16:43,030
catch them and punish them.

221
00:16:43,110 --> 00:16:44,440
-Me!
-Hey, me!

222
00:16:44,530 --> 00:16:45,820
Mr. Suzuki.

223
00:16:47,200 --> 00:16:51,030
Then the hall monitor
should also be punished for running.

224
00:16:51,120 --> 00:16:52,330
He's right! He's right!

225
00:16:52,990 --> 00:16:54,330
Way to go!

226
00:16:54,700 --> 00:16:56,080
He's right.

227
00:16:56,160 --> 00:16:57,580
Miss Tani.

228
00:16:58,500 --> 00:17:02,800
The hall monitor
shouldn't be punished because...

229
00:17:04,090 --> 00:17:08,590
it's like a policeman
chasing a speeding car.

230
00:17:15,140 --> 00:17:17,020
Any objections?

231
00:17:19,230 --> 00:17:20,940
A policeman?

232
00:17:21,020 --> 00:17:22,310
No more running.

233
00:17:23,230 --> 00:17:28,240
So, the hall monitor can chase offenders.

234
00:17:30,700 --> 00:17:32,070
Any other issues?

235
00:17:32,530 --> 00:17:33,370
Here.

236
00:17:33,450 --> 00:17:34,330
Miss Tani.

237
00:17:35,540 --> 00:17:37,040
-Her again.
-Busybody.

238
00:17:37,120 --> 00:17:38,330
Be quiet.

239
00:17:38,410 --> 00:17:40,830
Some people don't finish lunch.

240
00:17:41,540 --> 00:17:45,800
I just read an article on the Vietnam War.

241
00:17:46,550 --> 00:17:50,180
There are
many unfortunate people overseas.

242
00:17:50,260 --> 00:17:51,680
We're very lucky.

243
00:17:51,970 --> 00:17:53,640
Lucky to have you near me!

244
00:17:57,060 --> 00:18:00,140
We should be grateful for our food.

245
00:18:00,560 --> 00:18:05,270
We're allowed to leave
one thing on our plates,

246
00:18:05,940 --> 00:18:07,150
but I think it's wrong!

247
00:18:09,900 --> 00:18:12,360
Goody two-shoes.

248
00:18:13,030 --> 00:18:17,620
-It can't hurt to leave one thing.
-Let's all leave milk...

249
00:18:17,700 --> 00:18:20,830
-Give it to someone else...
-Of course.

250
00:18:20,910 --> 00:18:24,790
-People hide leftovers in bread.
-That's cheating!

251
00:18:25,250 --> 00:18:27,500
-I hate school food.
-Order!

252
00:18:27,590 --> 00:18:29,840
If you want to speak, raise your hand!

253
00:18:30,760 --> 00:18:33,260
What a revolting situation.

254
00:18:36,220 --> 00:18:39,980
<i>That night in bed,</i>
<i>after chatting to my sisters,</i>

255
00:18:41,440 --> 00:18:44,810
<i>more memories from fifth grade</i>

256
00:18:44,900 --> 00:18:48,070
<i>came rushing back.</i>

257
00:18:51,450 --> 00:18:55,820
<i>Our pet dog... School sports day...</i>

258
00:18:57,030 --> 00:18:59,240
<i>Being scared by gross horror comics...</i>

259
